6,0.17449941,-0.00083378,0.01576445,0.06261826,0.00111118,0.07906134,-0.01557379,0.04102552,-0.00327776,-0.00044541,0.08058433,-0.05795565,0.03710131,0.00830044,0.02055160,0.01111413,0.02963028,-0.06533545,-0.05408719,0.01543374,0.00336022,0.01242024,0.00290200,0.06509690,-0.03667070,-0.10339297,-0.04732184,0.05233400,-0.09185080,-0.02568236,0.03666779,0.02941020,0.05211489,-0.00346465,0.00576879,0.00390587,-0.04999458,0.02553830,0.05155993,-0.03216022,0.02260483,-0.01598614,-0.01090474]',E'Replicated and Distributed Queues {#distributed}\n\nThis general rule applies to all messaging data types supported by RabbitMQ except for one.\n[Streams](./streams) are an exception to this rule, and require clients, regardless of the protocol they use, to connect to a node\nthat hosts a replica (a leader of rollower) of the target stream.\nConsequently, RabbitMQ Stream protocol clients will [connect to multiple nodes in parallel](./stream-connections).\n\nQueues can also be [federated](./federated-queues)\nacross loosely coupled nodes or clusters.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Queues", "section_title": "queues", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/queues.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,queues", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
