336385,0.03750369,0.00615047,0.03508171,-0.01513960,0.04291982,-0.00811316,0.00718968,-0.00464249,0.02025615,0.05078679,-0.04656130,0.04869561,-0.11513245,-0.06107675,0.00244404,-0.00502078,-0.02176350,-0.05708236,0.02252929,0.02038133,-0.02406026,0.07287531,0.02811576,-0.06160005,-0.12087453,-0.04725099,0.05134377,-0.04148154,-0.04810821,0.02120206,0.01096325,0.10428076,0.02775364,0.00989803,-0.00235350,-0.00973780,0.00376337,0.03766229,0.05386460,0.04525326,-0.01532388,-0.00103061]',E'Avoid Temporary Queues with Well-Known Names {#shared-temporary-queues}\n\nAs the failed connection which had the only consumer on an auto-delete queue,\nthe queue must be deleted by RabbitMQ. This operation will take some time,\nduring which the consumer may recover.\n\nThen depending on the timing of operations, the queue can be\n\n1. Declared by the recovering client and then deleted\n2. Deleted and then re-declared\n\nIn the first case, the client will try to re-register its consumer on a queue that''s\nbeen concurrently deleted, which will lead to a channel exception.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Queues", "section_title": "queues", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/queues.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,queues", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
