.18111421,-0.00733773,0.03980664,0.00240213,-0.02973135,0.08250262,-0.03768894,-0.01800434,-0.04540113,-0.03155958,0.03318688,-0.02776794,0.05080017,-0.05296581,-0.00583508,0.00622480,-0.00182766,0.00998785,-0.05464950,0.00250668,0.00094045,0.01205722,0.05340140,0.00716275,-0.02318787,-0.09730206,-0.01862813,0.03635424,-0.06302382,-0.06121088,0.01027947,0.03502618,0.10342644,-0.00728481,0.03719253,-0.03656918,-0.02870112,0.00209355,0.01239313,-0.00073797,0.03538140,-0.01611093,-0.01659852]',E'Avoid Temporary Queues with Well-Known Names {#shared-temporary-queues}\n\nThere are two solutions to this fundamental race condition:\n\n1. Introduce a connection recovery delay. For example, several RabbitMQ client libraries\n   use a connection recovery delay of 5 seconds by default\n2. Use server-named queues, which side steps the problem entirely since the new client connection\n   will use a different queue name from its predecessor','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Queues", "section_title": "queues", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/queues.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,queues", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
