36748,0.03499721,0.01978833,-0.00238566,-0.06566144,0.04995142,0.04138971,0.02607738,0.07405534,-0.02828262,0.03792603,-0.04670875,0.01602154,-0.03453803,0.02176003,0.05019717,-0.01014702,0.01785797,-0.12232339,0.01793422,-0.02147949,0.00665630,0.03052327,0.03390886,-0.04452599,-0.09545186,-0.05585436,0.00107931,-0.01663563,0.00262954,0.02681476,-0.00718702,-0.00219454,-0.01106542,-0.06916235,-0.00730733,-0.01833518,0.01822041,0.05098860,0.01965102,-0.01247067,-0.00468853,-0.00495252]',E'What is an Exchange?\n\nIn AMQP 0-9-1, exchanges are the entities where [publishers](./publishers) publish\nmessages that are then routed to a set of queues or [streams](./streams).\n\nExchanges, like other topology elements in AMQP 0-9-1, are declared by applications\nusing client libraries.\n\nThe purpose of exchanges is to route all messages that flow through them to one or more [queues](./queues),\n[streams](./streams), or other exchanges.\n\nThe type of the exchange and the binding properties are used to implement the routing logic.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Exchanges", "section_title": "exchanges", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/exchanges.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,exchanges", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
