30,0.10716181,-0.04099566,0.06727133,0.02834927,0.00978254,0.06344442,-0.03077895,0.03175548,0.05595955,-0.02254032,0.02176518,-0.01422950,0.03027957,-0.03563857,0.02515245,0.00805903,0.04448261,-0.05227005,-0.01668851,0.01323169,0.01193539,-0.01465587,0.03924610,-0.00149875,-0.08365747,-0.12135731,0.03354498,0.00354056,-0.04233507,-0.05304359,0.03588511,0.01571863,-0.02564654,0.05374186,0.04365614,-0.04685871,-0.02350677,0.01397083,0.06486592,-0.02629339,0.05262725,0.03865235,0.00912109]',E'What Can Fail? {#what-can-fail}\n\nMessaging-based systems are distributed by definition and can fail in\ndifferent, and sometimes subtle, ways.\n\nNetwork connection problems and congestion are probably the most common class of failure.\nNot only can networks fail, [firewalls can interrupt connections](./heartbeats#tcp-proxies)\nthey consider to be idle, and network failures [take time to detect](./heartbeats).','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Reliability Guide", "section_title": "reliability", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/reliability.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,reliability", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
