86591,0.18395010,-0.03989457,0.01348303,0.01092348,0.01176433,0.05802033,-0.06146247,0.00740092,-0.00251498,-0.01271333,0.06751005,-0.00660148,-0.00133798,-0.03410793,0.06413772,0.06739615,0.04341281,-0.02011414,-0.02578002,0.03502923,0.01334284,-0.00154487,0.02802068,-0.01096007,-0.01533530,-0.03869051,-0.05028946,0.02982750,-0.05322407,-0.03527214,0.00044505,-0.00630794,0.01829903,0.05736359,-0.04762531,0.03497092,-0.04172717,0.04583085,0.02603907,0.03235179,0.06208241,0.00665145,0.00085914]',E'Clustering and Queue Content Replication {#clustering}\n\nQueues and streams remain visible and reachable from all nodes regardless\nof what node their leader replica is located. During a leader re-election, in flight\nmessage delivery will be paused for quorum queues until a new leader is elected.\nIn the case of a successful leader election, this happens transparently to clients.\n\n[Exclusive queues](./queues#exclusive-queues) are tied to the lifecycle of their connection and thus are never\nreplicated and by definition will not survive a node restart.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Reliability Guide", "section_title": "reliability", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/reliability.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,reliability", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
