4156,0.02185212,-0.00920987,0.00152707,-0.03475451,0.07262507,-0.02891641,-0.02890919,0.00200404,-0.04968419,0.03376963,0.02033130,0.03832462,-0.01950279,0.01793511,0.02148784,-0.01245710,-0.01144885,-0.04438891,-0.00582702,0.01652704,0.00039236,0.05927690,-0.02557521,-0.04356693,-0.03669534,-0.00349032,0.03424622,-0.05031244,-0.01691628,0.00457328,-0.04388899,-0.00035241,0.03022282,-0.00989548,-0.03707283,-0.08477443,0.03394280,0.03039831,-0.00696510,0.03714918,0.01565403,-0.02302945]',E'Ensuring that Messages are Routed {#routing}\n\nProducers should also be aware that when publishing to a clustered node,\nif one or more destination queues that are bound to the exchange have\nmirrors in the cluster, it''s possible to incur delays in the face of\nnetwork failures between nodes, due to flow control between replicas\nand the queue leader replica. See [inter-node heartbeat guide](./nettick) for\nmore details.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Reliability Guide", "section_title": "reliability", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/reliability.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,reliability", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
