77,0.15446457,0.03119046,-0.06471424,0.03471971,0.00581189,0.04225629,-0.01566290,0.03767580,-0.02520844,0.01047226,0.05167458,-0.05116439,0.04422613,-0.05307651,0.04974538,-0.01573866,0.03351501,0.01097322,-0.04759028,-0.00317778,0.01954776,-0.04314312,0.04751347,-0.00897582,-0.08170151,-0.05804351,-0.00718785,0.04574183,-0.05036763,-0.06643558,-0.00046575,-0.01765418,-0.02894229,-0.00827114,-0.03527261,0.01474532,-0.00253843,0.01256284,0.07053024,0.00504538,0.04005899,-0.00139808,-0.00847637]',E'Data Safety on the Consumer Side {#consumer-side}\n\nIn the event of network failure (or a node failure), messages can be\n[redelivered](./consumers#message-properties), and consumers must be prepared to handle\ndeliveries they have seen in the past. It is recommended that consumer implementation\nis designed to be idempotent rather than to explicitly\nperform deduplication.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Reliability Guide", "section_title": "reliability", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/reliability.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,reliability", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
