,-0.03504038,0.00740768,0.02723731,-0.02473008,0.08587862,0.00408925,0.02081730,0.00829374,0.02957343,0.06885450,-0.03769800,-0.00146178,-0.03870833,0.01492016,-0.02201567,0.00067844,-0.01131752,-0.04857307,-0.01006978,-0.06711105,0.01902059,0.03353892,-0.02166482,-0.03976233,-0.10089295,0.00754865,0.02909356,-0.10168940,-0.00854791,-0.05117514,-0.00417597,0.05930427,-0.01704243,0.04502095,-0.00959015,-0.07366528,-0.06206141,-0.01172048,0.00049323,0.06454974,0.03948137,0.00344613]',E'Node Names (Identifiers) {#node-names}\n\nRabbitMQ nodes are identified by node names. A node name consists of two parts,\na prefix (usually `rabbit`) and hostname. For example, `rabbit@node1.messaging.svc.local`\nis a node name with the prefix of `rabbit` and hostname of `node1.messaging.svc.local`.\n\nNode names in a cluster must be unique. If more than one node is running on a given host\n(this is usually the case in development and QA environments), they must use\ndifferent prefixes, e.g. `rabbit1@hostname` and `rabbit2@hostname`.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
