4599,-0.00062045,-0.01657359,0.04870840,0.01798180,0.07620201,-0.00408580,0.04803517,-0.00596367,-0.04194127,0.04357337,0.00385636,0.01864681,0.07314220,0.04293343,-0.01535888,0.01784579,-0.01681532,0.00282424,-0.06491257,-0.00765999,0.03697758,0.06444331,-0.04035691,0.01884316,-0.05440470,0.06151844,-0.02399527,-0.06095289,-0.03605571,0.00790831,0.01533338,0.02411106,-0.00534135,-0.01614301,0.00639968,-0.05480236,-0.00260492,0.01055771,0.02253213,0.04206926,-0.01911068,0.03224917]',E'Hostname Resolution {#hostname-resolution-requirement}\n\nNodes will perform hostname resolution early on node boot.\nIn container-based environments it is important that hostname\nresolution is ready before the container is started.\nFor Kubernetes users, this means the [DNS cache interval for CoreDNS](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset/#stable-network-id)\nto a value in the 5-10 second range.\n\nHostname resolution can use any of the standard OS-provided\nmethods:\n\n * DNS records\n * Local host files (e.g. `/etc/hosts`)','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
