8076,0.00020312,-0.01671067,0.04372577,0.01005533,0.06831294,-0.02910309,0.00566925,0.00149932,-0.01156100,0.05650378,0.00638825,0.00714007,-0.01000404,0.02029597,0.06521164,0.02405383,0.01404485,-0.10439022,-0.00757706,0.02149214,0.02034085,0.03813005,-0.00575657,-0.05726092,-0.12981668,-0.05162168,0.03552626,-0.07739934,0.00671410,0.01770278,-0.00455380,0.03000965,-0.00356135,-0.02280435,-0.00511513,-0.03545037,0.04814582,0.05619656,0.03177629,0.04053583,-0.00150362,-0.01645542]',E'What is Replicated? {#overview-what-is-replicated}\n\nAll data/state required for the operation of a RabbitMQ\nbroker is replicated across all nodes. An exception to this\nare message queues, which by default reside on one node,\nthough they are visible and reachable from all nodes. To\nreplicate queues across nodes in a cluster, use a queue type\nthat supports replication. This topic is covered in\nthe [Quorum Queues](./quorum-queues) guide.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
