689,-0.00808804,0.01324419,-0.01045334,0.04600395,0.04957890,0.04414743,0.01531784,0.01738587,-0.00938251,-0.02865776,0.04511318,-0.02662043,-0.02582892,-0.06017611,-0.01818244,-0.01420231,-0.08147242,0.02607149,-0.03814628,-0.02280761,0.07119834,-0.04367953,-0.02984874,-0.06864931,0.06937236,-0.02128505,-0.02528289,-0.03109109,-0.01222688,0.01136463,0.04233124,0.02621446,0.00828882,-0.05326355,-0.10091089,-0.07464924,0.00289946,0.01415014,0.09448567,-0.03938127,-0.01236546]',E'Linux, MacOS, *BSD\n\nOn UNIX systems, the cookie will be typically\nlocated in `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie` (used by the server)\nand `$HOME/.erlang.cookie` (used by CLI tools). Note that since the value\nof `$HOME` varies from user to user, it''s necessary to place a copy of\nthe cookie file for each user that will be using the CLI tools.\nThis applies to both non-privileged users and `root`.\n\nRabbitMQ nodes will log its effective user''s home directory location early on boot.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
