8893765,0.07360963,0.01179751,0.02252430,-0.02144081,0.02405543,0.05749936,0.02817519,0.00314213,0.03608437,-0.00907706,-0.02353260,0.06272771,-0.01224214,-0.00263499,-0.00427661,-0.01628816,-0.05547580,-0.07038168,-0.01215078,-0.00605474,-0.01769914,0.06883927,-0.06479399,-0.01548165,-0.05053377,0.03975087,0.03445124,-0.01995852,-0.02205630,-0.01869204,0.02561546,0.02191758,0.00020598,0.01345924,-0.06894542,-0.10339598,-0.07830161,0.03215351,0.00446360,0.13700642,-0.02389519,-0.02377258]',E'Troubleshooting {#cookie-file-troubleshooting}\n\nWhen a node starts, it will [log](./logging) the home directory location of its effective user:\n\n```\nnode           : rabbit@cdbf4de5f22d\nhome dir       : /var/lib/rabbitmq\n```\n\nUnless any [server directories](./relocate) were overridden, that''s the directory where\nthe cookie file will be looked for, and created by the node on first boot if it does not already exist.\n\nIn the example above, the cookie file location will be `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie`.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
