455,0.03455726,-0.02651781,0.03950375,0.04444914,0.04508955,0.02745380,0.04342498,-0.03221160,-0.01273851,0.02407153,-0.02597490,0.06065459,-0.02742705,-0.01339330,-0.02862138,0.02224169,-0.03851574,-0.06490724,0.05880181,0.02364310,-0.01235324,0.05096261,-0.01989837,0.02018361,-0.08667286,0.06654482,0.01245465,-0.09408931,-0.10279010,0.03196718,0.04392547,-0.00705991,0.08105837,0.07265150,-0.03865173,-0.05651048,-0.03094031,0.03511783,0.00767190,0.06037697,-0.02951218,-0.01825900]',E'Authentication Failures {#peer-authentication-failures}\n\nWhen a CLI tool such as `rabbitmqctl` fails to authenticate with RabbitMQ,\nthe message usually says\n\n```\n* epmd reports node ''rabbit'' running on port 25672\n* TCP connection succeeded but Erlang distribution failed\n* suggestion: hostname mismatch?\n* suggestion: is the cookie set correctly?\n* suggestion: is the Erlang distribution using TLS?\n```\n\nAn incorrectly placed cookie file or cookie value mismatch are most common scenarios for such failures.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
