,0.17250620,-0.00656216,-0.00612195,0.04891303,0.05149865,0.05219540,-0.00337894,0.01500457,-0.03099090,-0.02132051,0.04119358,-0.04846862,0.03569202,0.04985048,0.02405857,0.01843076,0.03541737,-0.03368995,-0.02781363,-0.02671413,-0.01000566,0.03011920,0.04187064,0.01258776,0.02668954,-0.04635443,0.05010028,-0.00971895,-0.11816280,-0.03589667,0.03138776,-0.01086841,0.02847729,0.05447690,-0.00954616,0.03534825,-0.02306491,0.00641994,0.02428325,-0.02014998,0.08302740,0.01256744,-0.00418686]',E'Hostname Resolution\n\nSince hostname resolution is a [prerequisite for successful inter-node communication](#hostname-resolution-requirement),\nstarting with [RabbitMQ `3.8.6`](/release-information), CLI tools provide two commands that help verify\nthat hostname resolution on a node works as expected. The commands are not meant to replace\n[`dig`](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dig_(command)) and other specialised DNS tools but rather\nprovide a way to perform most basic checks while taking [Erlang runtime hostname resolver features](https://erlang.org/doc/apps/erts/inet_cfg.html)\ninto account.\n\nThe commands are covered in the [Networking guide](./networking#dns-verify-resolution).','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
