16474663,0.03316992,0.05232106,0.07462541,-0.03959941,0.08617152,0.00166135,0.05499195,-0.02400224,0.02441149,0.08611119,-0.03814388,0.03464994,-0.00915863,0.05106011,-0.02440085,0.00688279,-0.03281034,-0.02781708,0.01837270,-0.01815526,-0.02199453,0.04083219,0.04797209,-0.05404199,-0.08020075,-0.03437437,0.03444829,-0.11158099,-0.01909701,0.01146346,0.04375843,0.07330833,0.02503207,-0.02862772,-0.04141014,-0.04822168,0.03479686,0.04542670,0.01530793,0.05067933,0.01134821,-0.01298176]',E'Stream Clients\n\nRabbitMQ Stream protocol clients **behave differently from messaging protocols clients**: they are\nmore cluster topology-aware. For publishing, they can connect to any node, and that node\nwill forward all relevant operations to the node that hosts the leader replica of the stream.\n\nHowever, stream consumers should connect to one of the nodes hosting the replicas of\nthe target stream. The protocol includes a topology discovery operation, so well-behaved client\nlibraries will select one of the suitable nodes. This won''t be the case when a load balancer is used,\nhowever.\n\nSee the [stream client connection guide](./stream-connections) to learn more.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
