9,-0.00981496,0.04860485,0.05060813,0.01871561,0.09268950,-0.04477834,0.02774621,-0.03292439,-0.00256709,0.04286922,0.00951613,0.03461830,-0.03381771,0.02042734,-0.05218676,-0.00279746,-0.02971238,-0.00836226,0.05437967,0.03524607,0.02595735,0.07131288,-0.00751124,-0.01461329,-0.03295711,0.01976104,0.00347322,-0.09272156,-0.01254024,0.02414865,-0.02708329,0.01657404,0.05542880,-0.03182059,-0.02982920,-0.08050960,0.01758426,0.07884670,-0.02516399,0.04603463,-0.02242543,-0.00737342]',E'Queue and Stream Leader Replica Placement {#replica-placement}\n\n:::tip\nUsing `client-local` strategy is usually a good choice if the connections that declare queues\nare evenly distributed between nodes. In such case, even though the queue/leaders are placed locally\n(where the connection is), they are well balanced within the cluster. Otherwise, prefer the `balanced` strategy.\nThe disadvantage of the `balanced` strategy is that the connection that declared the queue may not have\nthe best possible performance when using this queues,','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
