,-0.01419733,0.01797127,0.04600976,0.01059883,0.04035954,-0.01344031,-0.00286926,-0.03193088,0.00891367,0.05719880,-0.00827992,0.02245625,-0.04917730,0.01746340,0.04928548,0.04997320,-0.03609220,-0.06387284,0.01736018,0.03622830,-0.03512894,0.07079738,-0.01269548,-0.05346968,-0.11092443,-0.02323179,0.04759588,-0.04336905,-0.00927877,-0.01508843,-0.00636764,-0.02478671,0.03435803,0.02150188,0.01325668,-0.06025024,0.00558271,0.05979429,0.02326083,0.03901843,0.02387563,0.00402031]',E'Node Failure Handling {#clustering-dealing-with-failure}\n\nRabbitMQ brokers tolerate the failure of individual\nnodes. Nodes can be started and stopped at will,\nas long as they can contact a cluster member node\nknown at the time of shutdown.\n\n[Quorum queue](./quorum-queues) allows queue contents to be replicated\nacross multiple cluster nodes with parallel replication and a predictable [leader election](./quorum-queues#leader-election)\nand [data safety](./quorum-queues#data-safety) behavior as long as a majority of replicas are online.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
