76,0.02228373,0.02703503,0.06430046,-0.00781619,0.01065344,-0.00357307,0.03870697,-0.07264817,0.01578514,0.07673000,-0.00173161,0.03679545,0.01640235,0.01792784,0.00834899,0.02392936,-0.04043183,-0.08489605,-0.00809073,0.06435740,0.04552593,0.07375087,0.02457316,0.01125338,-0.12715910,0.01586987,0.00880361,-0.10519239,-0.01413170,-0.01033546,0.00617871,0.03435099,0.01419571,0.06067943,0.01202383,-0.02737972,-0.00289725,0.02187463,-0.03172888,0.06456938,0.03058970,-0.00304612]',E'Creating a Cluster without [Peer Discovery](./cluster-formation) {#creating}\n\nManual cluster formation (`rabbitmqctl join_cluster`) is highly prone to human error and race conditions. Manual CLI joins should be strictly reserved for local development, testing, or specific edge-case recovery scenarios.\n\n:::\n\nIn order to link up our three nodes in a cluster, we tell\ntwo of the nodes, say `rabbit@rabbit2` and\n`rabbit@rabbit3`, to join the cluster of the\nthird, say `rabbit@rabbit1`.\n\nWe first join `rabbit@rabbit2` in a cluster with `rabbit@rabbit1`.\n\n:::danger','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
