105723,-0.02185815,0.04520086,-0.00128819,-0.04770065,0.02693979,0.02059569,-0.00511431,-0.01848780,0.01162294,0.01069159,-0.02973250,0.01638279,-0.03559666,0.01492699,-0.00643681,0.01242430,-0.07150832,-0.01139772,-0.01340347,0.04272855,-0.04911469,0.08720472,-0.03820196,-0.03719637,-0.09209494,-0.00559012,0.07560360,-0.08328228,-0.02797154,-0.05384637,-0.01040463,0.03489336,0.04106331,0.06459557,0.02209181,-0.01745220,-0.03140191,0.01001011,0.01829937,0.05204761,0.02598136,0.03631162]',E'How to Remove a Node from the Cluster {#removing-nodes}\n\nSometimes it is necessary to remove a node from the cluster.\n\nThe sequence of actions will be slightly different for the following\nmost common scenarios:\n\n * The node is online and reachable\n * The node is offline and cannot be recovered\n\nIn addition, if the cluster [peer discovery mechanisms](./cluster-formation)\nsupport node health checks and [forced removal of nodes](./cluster-formation#node-health-checks-and-cleanup) not known to the discovery backend.\n\nThat feature is opt-in (deactivated by default).\n\nContinuing with the three node cluster example used in this guide,\nlet''s demonstrate how to remove `rabbit@rabbit3` from the cluster, returning it to\nindependent operation.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
