907301,0.00798079,0.01052676,0.02522955,0.00988209,0.04624406,0.02169999,0.03817352,-0.04737392,0.03255116,0.01957235,0.02353263,0.01615371,-0.05347539,-0.00061243,0.00051000,0.02372404,-0.05633536,-0.04402149,0.01884625,-0.01959253,0.00194392,0.10764877,0.00158158,-0.01086998,-0.09249397,-0.01271057,0.06716897,-0.08521372,-0.00719726,0.03086032,-0.01561583,0.00270585,-0.02053004,-0.02756442,0.01172698,-0.02442954,-0.01072303,0.05057239,0.00339766,0.04918007,-0.02190036,-0.02043699]',E'Resetting a Node to Re-add It as a Brand New Node to Its Original Cluster\n\nA reset node that was [removed from the cluster](#removing-nodes) can be re-added to its original\ncluster as a brand new node.\n\nIn that case it will sync all virtual hosts, users, permissions and topology (queues, exchanges, bindings),\nruntime parameters and policies.\n\nFor [quorum queue](./quorum-queues) and [stream](./streams) contents to be replicated to the new [re]added node,\nthe node must be added to the list of nodes to place replicas on using `rabbitmq-queues grow`.\n\nNon-replicated queue and stream contents on a reset node will be lost.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
