13439,0.16986808,-0.00267876,0.06653871,0.02207568,-0.01730174,0.11579295,-0.03099397,0.08855179,-0.06035763,0.00226320,0.05824945,-0.06571706,0.04076890,0.01117495,0.00995010,-0.03938088,0.02621079,-0.03186191,-0.08051255,-0.03998840,-0.08217656,0.03204248,0.06916951,0.01777401,0.00698481,-0.07902575,0.02718596,0.04584255,-0.14056198,-0.01833310,-0.00080748,0.03548801,0.00724583,-0.02232998,-0.00022685,-0.01985904,-0.01559682,-0.01827991,0.04201539,0.03964900,0.04800821,0.02340781,-0.03071619]',E'Hostname Changes {#issues-hostname}\n\nRabbitMQ nodes use hostnames to communicate with each other. Therefore,\nall node names must be able to resolve names of all cluster peers. This is\nalso true for tools such as `rabbitmqctl`.\n\nIn addition to that, by default RabbitMQ names the database directory using the\ncurrent hostname of the system. If the hostname\nchanges, a new empty database is created. To avoid data loss it''s\ncrucial to set up a fixed and resolvable hostname.\n\nWhenever the hostname changes RabbitMQ node must be restarted.','{"source": "rabbitmq", "version": "3.13", "language": "amqp", "title": "Clustering Guide", "section_title": "clustering", "url": "https://github.com/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-website/blob/main/docs/clustering.md", "topics": "rabbitmq,messaging,clustering", "categories": "messaging,queue,amqp"}');
